            "parts": [
              "\ue203In the United States legal system, a **judicial panel** typically refers to a group of judges convened to hear and decide cases, especially in appellate courts.\ue204 \ue203These panels are most commonly composed of three judges and are standard in federal appellate courts, including the U.S. Courts of Appeals.\ue204 \ue203The practice of using three-judge panels has been in place since as early as 1891, as outlined in 28 U.S.C. \u00a7 46(c) \ue200cite\ue202turn0search12\ue201.\ue204\ue206\n\n\ue203In certain specialized contexts, such as the **Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation (JPML)**, the panel comprises seven federal judges appointed by the Chief Justice of the United States.\ue204 \ue203The JPML is responsible for determining whether civil actions pending in different federal districts should be transferred to a single district for coordinated or consolidated pretrial proceedings.\ue204 \ue203As of the latest available information, the current members of the JPML include:\ue204\ue206\n\n- \ue203**Karen K. Caldwell**, Chair \u2013 U.S. District Court, Eastern District of Kentucky\ue204\n- \ue203**Nathaniel M. Gorton** \u2013 U.S. District Court, District of Massachusetts\ue204\n- \ue203**Matthew F. Kennelly** \u2013 U.S. District Court, Northern District of Illinois\ue204\n- \ue203**David C. Norton** \u2013 U.S. District Court, District of South Carolina\ue204\n- \ue203**Roger T. Benitez** \u2013 U.S. District Court, Southern District of California\ue204\n- \ue203**Dale A. Kimball** \u2013 U.S. District Court, District of Utah\ue204\n- \ue203**Madeline Cox Arleo** \u2013 U.S. District Court, District of New Jersey\ue204 \ue200cite\ue202turn0search0\ue201\ue206\n\n\ue203These judges are selected to ensure a broad representation of geographic and judicial perspectives.\ue204 \ue203Their collective decisions can significantly influence the direction and efficiency of complex litigation across the country.\ue204\ue206\n\n\ue203In the context of your narrative, the concept of a \"judges panel\" could symbolically represent a collective of authoritative figures or archetypes that evaluate and influence the unfolding events.\ue204 \ue203Drawing parallels between the structured decision-making of judicial panels and"
